0.10 2026-05-20
    - made `dashboard telegram-codex.start` launch the listener in a stable
      two-way mode with a concise one-line Telegram acknowledgement for new
      inbound messages instead of the old passive startup behavior
    - kept direct `telegram-codex.listen` passive by default unless an
      explicit reply text is passed
    - made the listener survive transient `getUpdates` transport failures and
      clamp stale stored offsets up to the newer inbox-ledger offset so
      duplicated older Telegram updates are not replayed

0.09 2026-05-20
    - removed the listener's default placeholder auto-reply so
      `telegram-codex.listen` now captures inbound Telegram updates by
      default instead of sending `queued for Codex` bot messages
    - kept explicit listener acknowledgements available when a reply text
      is passed on the command line
    - updated the docs and Docker-verified TDD coverage to reflect the new
      passive-by-default listener behavior

0.08 2026-05-20
    - blocked duplicate Telegram reply spam by skipping any returned update
      whose `update_id` is older than the next stored session offset
    - added inbox-ledger offset recovery so a missing `listener.offset` file
      does not force the listener to replay stale Telegram backlog
    - added Docker-verified TDD coverage for stale-update skipping and
      inbox-ledger offset recovery in the always-on listener path

0.07 2026-05-20
    - finished the skill-owned `telegram-codex.start` launcher slice with
      Docker-verified coverage closure for the preserved saved-session and
      listener startup paths
    - fixed the listener anti-spam failure mode so a failed Telegram
      acknowledgement still advances the offset instead of replaying the
      same inbound message on every restart
    - kept the generated MCP bridge Python source as a standalone
      `scripts/telegram_mcp.py` asset instead of embedding it inside Perl
    - documented the covered-gate handling for the intentional child stdio
      redirection statements used only inside the background listener fork

0.06 2026-05-20
    - moved the real Telegram-aware Codex startup flow into
      `dashboard telegram-codex.start` and `./cli/start`
    - reduced `~/.developer-dashboard/cli/codex` and the user-PATH `codex`
      helper to thin handoff launchers into the skill-owned start command
    - preserved the original saved-session resume mapping from
      `TICKET_REF` and `~/.developer-dashboard/config/codex.json` inside
      the skill-owned start logic
    - added session-scoped listener pid/log paths to the runtime layout
      and updated the Docker-verified regressions and docs for the merged
      launcher ownership model

0.05 2026-05-20
    - fixed Codex auto-start integration so `dashboard skills install
      telegram-codex` provisions a managed `codex` wrapper in the user PATH
      instead of assuming `~/.developer-dashboard/cli/codex` is the active
      launcher
    - made managed `codex` auto-start prime the Telegram offset to the latest
      pending update on first start so old backlog messages do not get
      auto-replied and spam the chat
    - added a skill `Makefile` install hook so normal skill installation is
      enough to set up Telegram listener auto-start for later `codex` launches
    - updated the docs and Docker-verified regressions to prove the managed
      `codex` command path, session pid/log files, no-backlog auto-start
      behavior, and auto-setup behavior

0.04 2026-05-20
    - fixed the install docs to use `dashboard skills install telegram-codex`
      instead of a checkout path
    - made `dashboard telegram-codex.install` also write a `codex` launcher
      wrapper under `~/.developer-dashboard/cli/` that starts the Telegram
      listener automatically for the active Codex session before execing the
      real Codex binary
    - added Docker-verified regressions for the generated Codex wrapper,
      including session pid/log paths and real-binary handoff

0.03 2026-05-20
    - partitioned listener runtime state by Codex session id under
      `~/.telegram-codex/<session-id>/` so each Codex session keeps its own
      offset file and inbox ledger
    - added session-id precedence for `TELEGRAM_CODEX_SESSION_ID` over
      `CODEX_SESSION_ID`, with a safe `default` fallback when no session id
      is available
    - updated the listener docs, agent handoff guide, and Docker-verified
      regressions to prove session-specific state paths and listener output

0.02 2026-05-20
    - added `dashboard telegram-codex.listen` and `./cli/listen` for a
      long-poll always-on listener with persistent update offset state and
      local inbox ledger capture
    - made `TELEGRAM_BOT_TOKEN` discovery search the active project `.env`,
      parent/root `.env`, skill `.env`, and process environment so
      `dashboard telegram-codex...` can pick it up without an explicit export
    - documented the continuous listener workflow and bounded listener test
      mode, and added Docker-verified regression coverage for listener state,
      inbox logging, and executable wrapper behavior

0.01 2026-05-20
    - added the first packaged `telegram-codex` skill with install, get-me,
      updates, download, reply, send-photo, send-document, and `/start`
      auto-reply commands for a local Codex Telegram MCP bridge
    - added a generated stdio MCP plugin scaffold for Codex local plugin
      roots and local marketplace registration
    - added Docker-verified tests and 100% coverage proof for scaffold,
      Telegram API request shaping, CLI behavior, and release metadata
    - fixed the shipped CLI wrapper modes so the skill checkout entrypoints
      are executable and covered by regression tests
    - proved the live bot flow with install, get-me, updates, `/start`
      auto-reply, and direct reply evidence
